title: Elastic scattering of Be-9 on light target nuclei.

x4freetext: Elastic scattering of Be-9 on light target nuclei.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.313, p.376 (1979)

x4freetext: The ETH tandem accelerator was used.
Identification systems consisting of
dE-E solid state detector telescopes were used at
forward angles. At medium angles, where the decreasing
energies of Be-9 impeded the use of the telescopes, the
background was eliminated by measuring anticoincidences
between a thin detector having a thickness just
exceeding the range of the 9Be ions and a thick
detector placed immediately behind it. At large angles,
where the energy of the scattered ions is too low to
discriminate between the background in the thin
detector, coincidences between the Be-9 particles and
the recoil nuclei were used for identification. The
distances and entrance slits of both detectors were so
chosen that, in all the measurements, the solid angle
was determined by the Be-9 detector.
All targets showed a considerable carbon buildup of
about 0.8 mu-g/cm2 per hour with a 100 nA Be-9 beam.

x4freetext: The targets used in the experiments were
self-supporting with thicknesses of 50-70 mu-g/cm2 for
Be-9. The Be-9 targets contained 2-5% O-16 atoms and
5-10% C-12. The target thickness was equivalent to an
energy loss of 230 keV at 4.5 MeV and 140 keV at 11 MeV
Angle digitizing error
The relative errors are of the order of 10%, 5% and 15%
in the region of small, medium and large scattering
angles respectively.
